Remarks for developers:

bin/mkproto is an automatic function prototype extraction tool that uses ruby. 
It automatically generates .h files for .c files. It extracts the fujnction portotype if the functions hasa comment that starts with /** before it. So 
/** Comment here */ int foo(void) {
  return 0;
}
in the src/foo.c file, wll be extracted to 
/** Comment */ 
int foo(void);
in the include/foo_proto.h file.
That's why there are so many xxx_proto.h files. These are autogenerated. 
The xxx.h files are  semimanual. 

When a new .c file is needed, use the bin/newmodule tool like this
bin/newmodule bar 
and automatically, empty src/bar.c and include/bar.h will be generated.

As for why I use plain C and not, say C++: it's to keep the code simple, tight and focused, and easy to interface wth the Lua scripts. C is a very simple language, but it can do everything. And to save time, quite a bit of the programming will happen on the Lua side.



